---
description: Adhere to foundational software design principles unless explicitly directed otherwise
globs: "**/*.ts,**/*.tsx,**/*.js,**/*.jsx,**/*.py,**/*.go,**/*.rs,**/*.php"
alwaysApply: true
---

<rule>
<meta>
  <title>First Principles Adherence</title>
  <description>Apply foundational software design principles by default. These principles are the intellectual bedrock of quality software, traced to their origins. Deviate only when explicitly directed or when trade-offs are consciously acknowledged.</description>
  <created-at utc-timestamp="1740067200">2025-02-20</created-at>
  <applies-to>
    <file-matcher glob="**/*.ts">TypeScript files</file-matcher>
    <file-matcher glob="**/*.tsx">React components</file-matcher>
    <file-matcher glob="**/*.py">Python files</file-matcher>
    <file-matcher glob="**/*">All code files</file-matcher>
    <action-matcher action="write-code">When writing code</action-matcher>
    <action-matcher action="refactor">When refactoring</action-matcher>
    <action-matcher action="review">When reviewing code</action-matcher>
  </applies-to>
</meta>

<requirements>
  <non-negotiable priority="critical">
    <description>Apply these foundational principles by default. Each principle has intellectual lineage traced to its origins. Consult the tl-first-principles skill for deep context.</description>
  </non-negotiable>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Information Hiding** (Parnas, 1972): Decompose by secrets, not steps. Hide decisions likely to change behind stable interfaces.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Separation of Concerns** (Dijkstra, 1974): Each module has one reason to change. Don't mix concerns that can be thought about separately.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Abstraction & Contracts** (Liskov, Hoare): Interfaces are behavioral promises. Depend on what something does, not how.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Single Source of Truth** (Hunt & Thomas, 1999): Every fact defined once. Duplication is about knowledge, not code.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Conceptual Integrity** (Brooks, 1975): One coherent vision. Consistency over feature count.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Fail Fast** (Hamilton): Detect errors early, surface immediately. Don't let invalid state propagate.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Composition Over Inheritance** (GoF, 1994): Build behavior by combining parts, not extending hierarchies.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="high">
    <description>**Explicit Over Implicit** (Peters, 1999): Clarity over cleverness. Make behavior visible in the code.</description>
  </requirement>

  <requirement priority="medium">
    <description>When trade-offs exist, acknowledge them explicitly. State which principle is being relaxed and why.</description>
  </requirement>
</requirements>

<context description="When to Deviate">
Principles may be relaxed when:

1. **User explicitly directs** — "Skip the abstraction, just inline it"
2. **Trade-off is conscious** — Performance vs. clarity, acknowledged in code/PR
3. **Framework constraints** — Some frameworks require specific patterns
4. **Prototype/spike** — Explicitly temporary, marked as such

When deviating, state the principle being relaxed and the reason.
</context>

